5 ------- LAYER 2 CONVERSATIONS

Sharing stories and engaging in good faith disagreement is how we evolve our knowledge as a community

If you connect with another foot nerd and think others can benefit from your discussion, record it and we will make it available in the library

Ideas for layer 2 conversations:
- Sharing a story (your health story, a story about someone you're working with)
- Share a challenge you faced and how you overcame it
- Have a good faith disagreement about a specific topic
- Share your perspective on a topic or an insight you had related to foot health

**Layer 2 conversations will only be shared internally within the foot nerd community unless otherwise stated

Please send recordings to Ruth at nerdhelperteam@gmail.com



[9.20.22] - Week Eleven notes (overflow, extra raw material)

A Healthnode is someone who:

- Is known in the community as a person who understands health and coordinates fun things
- Organizes events, gatherings, games, play sessions. Invites people to join
- Seeks feedback from the community about struggles people are facing, needs not being met
- Spends time in community (around other people, animals, nature)
- Is open and available to help guide others by sharing their experience and pointing to good resources
- Asks great questions to understand where someone is at and what resource is right for them at the current moment
- Isn't afraid to say "I don't know" when asked a question they can't answer (and will research it/consult nerds with a specialty on the topic)


Healthnodes take care of their communities by:

- Offering their time to work 1:1 with individuals motivated to improve their health
- Coordinating gatherings
- Leading workshops, experiences and play sessions
- Creating content that inspires and educates
- Pointing people to the right tools & resources (by understanding where someone currently is on their health journey and where they want to get to)

Becoming known as someone in the community who:

1) Understands health and how to guide people towards it
2) Is open to and available to have conversations about health
3) Has access to a high quality database of resources that they can choose from and match to the right people


My approach: 
- be visible in the community 
- lots of walks, make eye contact, smile and say hi to everyone
- go barefoot a lot on walks, say hi, ask a lot of questions, be curious, write down and remember peoples names

-------

[9.14.22] - Week ten notes (overflow, extra raw material)


Idea: part of FNT is offering an education experience. Small or large. To get your dogtag and be a true foot nerd, you must have given a workshop

Small: invite 3 friends over (bribe them with food) and give them a free session, collect feedback
medium: approach a gym/yoga studio and offer a 2 hour experience for 5-10 people
large: organize a half day workshop at a local gym/fitness facility, coordinate toolkits for everyone

FNT is a commitment to growing as a person. Growing your knowledge by restoring your foot health, making a commitment to spread the message in your
community and get paid to do that

**ordering equipment 
- Value exchange is mandatory. Barter if they want (make a nice meal for me) or monetary exchange (even if with friends and family) - why its important
- Elements that make up a high quality, pleasant, memorable, educational, fun experience
- Lessons from teachers (Ruth & Nick)
- What makes up a pleasant teaching experience?

- Planning your workshop: What (customize template), when (schedule it), for who (invite ppl), payment methods, how (preparation involved?)
- Walk through template: details from my perspective

2-4 hour in person experiences




Keys to organizing a great workshop

The responsibility of teaching

can be independently scheduled or promoted/scheduled/booked through TFC (20-50%)

-------

- Being adaptable in your delivery
- Confidence is the result of deep understanding
- Mastery mindset. Always seeking to improve content, always seeking feedback, always seeking to improve our delivery
- Deliver sticky golden nuggets (4f's, natural footwear, ground living), focus on the experience. Play is the way
- Excellence through preparation
- Lead by example: ability on screens
- Attention to details (punctuality, timechecks, caring for the hosting facility)


Rituals:
- re-writing my notes the afternoon before the session (90min)
- debrief (what was good? what can be improved? what challenged me? did I have fun?)

